[00:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'printing uses a special ink that expands when heated, creating that raised 3D texture. That\'s why brands love it. It looks bold, premium, and it adds depth to simple designs, especially text. But'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'puff printing also means special inks, extra setup, and higher costs. This is where DTF comes in. With DTF, we can\'t chemically expand the ink, but we can'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fake the look. By designing the artwork the right way, we can create a visual puff effect that still looks thick, bold, and raised once it\'s pressed. This is perfect for small batches, on demand'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'orders, and creators who want that puff look without the extra hassle. Before we jump into KD, let\'s talk about why this works. A puff style design needs three things. Thick shapes, rounded edges, and'

[01:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'depth. Thin lines won\'t work. Sharp details won\'t work. We want bold text, soft curves, and shadows that make the design feel inflated. Why use KD? Because it makes this process fast.'

